ver into a non-technical overview of its ecology. Strayer describes the geography and geology of the Hudson and its basin, the properties of water and its movements in the river, water chemistry, and the river's plants and animals. He then takes a more detailed look at the Hudson's ecosystems and each of its major habitats. Strayer also discusses important management challenges facing the river today, including pollution, habitat destruction, overfishing, invasive species, and ecological restoration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aEnvironmental protectionxHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aEstuarine healthxHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aHuman ecologyxHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aNatural historyxHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aNaturexEffect of human beings onxHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aRestoration ecologyxHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aStream ecologyxHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aWaterxPollutionxHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 7aNATURE / Ecology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520952393423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520952393.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles